  m_Script: {fileID: 11500000, guid: 15c16d4c9e6a52544902df8577bd4ec7, type: 3}
  m_Name: 07_Micro
  m_EditorClassIdentifier: 
  questionText: Three bulbs of ratings (40W, 220V), (50W, 220V) and (60W, 220V) respectively
    are connected in parallel to a 220V mains. Then which of these bulbs will glow
    more?
  referenceImage: {fileID: 0}
  explanationText: "Actual power consumed \n\U0001D443\n=\n\U0001D449\n\U0001D460\n2\n\U0001D445\nP=\nR\nV\ns\n2\n\t\u200B\n\n\t\u200B\n\n
    where \n\U0001D449\n\U0001D460\nV\ns\n\t\u200B\n\n is the supply voltage and
    the resistance of electrical appliances \n\U0001D445\n=\n\U0001D449\n\U0001D45F\n2\n\U0001D443\n\U0001D45F\nR=\nP\nr\n\t\u200B\n\nV\nr\n2\n\t\u200B\n\n\t\u200B\n\n
    where \n\U0001D449\n\U0001D45F\nV\nr\n\t\u200B\n\n and \n\U0001D443\n\U0001D45F\nP\nr\n\t\u200B\n\n
    are the rated voltage and power respectively. So from these two equations we
    can say that a higher rating bulb will glow more."
  options:
  - (40 W, 220 V)
  - (60 W, 220 V)
  - (50 W, 220 V)
  - All will glow with the same brightness
  correctOptionIndex: 1
  correctDropId: 
  correctValue: 0
  tolerance: 0.1
